<h2>Solar Panels in Montana</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Montana's solar potential ranks among the top 15 states in the nation, with excellent solar irradiance levels particularly in the eastern two-thirds of the state. The Great Plains region of Montana receives between 4.5 to 5.2 peak sun hours daily on average, while western mountainous areas typically see 4.0 to 4.8 hours. Cities like Billings, Miles City, and Glendive experience some of the highest solar radiation levels in the northern United States, comparable to regions much further south. Even during winter months, Montana's high altitude and frequent clear skies provide substantial solar generation opportunities, with snow reflection often boosting panel performance.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Montana can produce between 1,200 to 1,400 kWh per kW of installed capacity annually. This means a 6kW system can generate approximately 7,200 to 8,400 kWh per year, often covering 60-80% of an average Montana household's electricity consumption. The state's northern latitude actually benefits summer solar production, with longer daylight hours from May through August compensating for the lower winter sun angle. Montana's dry climate also reduces atmospheric interference, allowing panels to operate at peak efficiency more frequently than in humid regions.</p>

