<h2>Montana Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Montana offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC installations that can significantly reduce upfront costs and improve return on investment. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, representing thousands of dollars in savings for most residential installations.</p>

<p>The state of Montana provides its own Alternative Energy Systems Tax Credit, offering up to \$500 for residential solar installations and \$1,000 for commercial projects. While modest compared to some states, this credit can be combined with federal incentives and utility rebates. Montana also exempts solar equipment from state sales tax and offers property tax incentives that prevent solar installations from increasing property tax assessments, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime.</p>

<p>NorthWestern Energy, Montana's largest utility, offers several programs supporting energy efficiency and renewable energy. Their Energy Efficiency Programs provide rebates ranging from \$50-500 for qualifying HVAC equipment, including high-efficiency furnaces, heat pumps, and air conditioning systems. The utility's Universal System Benefits Programs fund additional incentives for renewable energy projects and energy efficiency improvements. Net metering policies allow solar customers to receive credit for excess electricity production, typically at the retail electricity rate, making solar installations more financially attractive.</p>

<p>Many local utilities and cooperatives throughout Montana offer additional rebates and incentives. For example, Flathead Electric Cooperative provides rebates up to \$600 for heat pump water heaters and additional incentives for solar installations. PPL Montana offers efficiency rebates for HVAC upgrades, and many municipal utilities provide their own incentive programs. Property owners should research all available local, state, and federal incentives as they can often be combined to substantially reduce project costs.</p>

